<subSubSection id="33CB651CFFB6FFF65BE9FE9DE33BFECD" box="[240,1143,291,315]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="7B6E3697FFB6FFF65BE9FE9DE33BFECD" blockId="23.[192,1440,195,539]" box="[240,1143,291,315]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFB6FFF65BE9FE9DE6C0FECD" bold="true" box="[240,396,291,315]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after its prominently convex hindwing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="33CB651CFFB6FFF65BE9FEFDE608FE8D" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7B6E3697FFB6FFF65BE9FEFDE608FE8D" blockId="23.[192,1440,195,539]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFB6FFF65BE9FEFDE53BFEAD" bold="true" box="[240,631,323,347]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Distribution and phenology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFB6FFF65964FEFDE4EBFEAD" authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[637,935,323,347]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexus">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFB6FFF65964FEFDE4EBFEAD" box="[637,935,323,347]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Porphyrogenes convexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus id="A46A8835FFB6FFF65FD3FEFDE278FEAD" box="[1226,1332,323,347]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">holotype</typeStatus>
taken in November.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="33CB651CFFB6FFF65BE9FE3DE55DFDED" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7B6E3697FFB6FFF65BE9FE3DE55DFDED" blockId="23.[192,1440,195,539]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFB6FFF65BE9FE3DE51FFE6D" bold="true" box="[240,595,387,411]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis and discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFB6FFF65940FE3DE4CCFE6D" authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[601,896,387,411]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexus">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFB6FFF65940FE3DE4CCFE6D" box="[601,896,387,411]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Porphyrogenes convexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily recognized by the extreme convexity of the hindwing similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFB6FFF65993FE1AE458FE4D" authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1871" box="[650,788,419,443]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Telegonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="omphale">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFB6FFF65993FE1AE458FE4D" box="[650,788,419,443]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">P. omphale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and by the dark and contrasting anterior tuft on the dorsal hindwing. The genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFB6FFF65946FE7AE5A1FE2D" authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[607,749,452,475]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexus">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFB6FFF65946FE7AE5A1FE2D" box="[607,749,452,475]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">P. convexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very different from any heretofore described species with the harpe having an expanded and dentate caudal end, but generally similar to those of an additional five species described below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
